<div class="f14 metric" style="color:#656668;display:flex;"><img src="/assets/images/calendar.png" style="height:12px;margin-top:auto;margin-bottom:auto;"><span class="updateDate">&nbsp; Updated on 24/01/2019</span> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="/assets/images/updated.png" style="height:12px;margin-top:auto;margin-bottom:auto;"><span class="readTime">&nbsp; 3 minutes to read</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><br><div class="mw-parser-output"><p><br>
This section provides steps integrate Cloud Optimizer (CO) 3.03 and containerized OpsBridge Manager (OBM) that is part of OpsB 2018.11 suite. 
</p><p><b>Step 1: Import the CO Management Pack package into OBM</b>
</p>
<ol><li>Log on to the CO user interface in any of the supported browser and navigate to <b>Settings &gt; Integration</b>.</li>
<li>Scroll down and click <b>Download ZIP Package (OMi)</b> to download the OBM package: <br> <a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="OpsB 2018.05 1.jpg" src="/mediawiki/images/e/e0/OpsB_2018.05_1.jpg" width="306" height="105" data-file-width="306" data-file-height="105"></a> <br></li>
<li>Prepare the package for upload.</li>
<li>Extract the downloaded file to the path shown below. Copy the file <i>OMi_Integration_Pack_for_vPV.zip</i> into the <b>OMi pod</b>. <br> <a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="OpsB 2018.05 2.jpg" src="/mediawiki/images/2/24/OpsB_2018.05_2.jpg" width="470" height="133" data-file-width="470" data-file-height="133"></a> <br></li>
<li>Copy this file into a temp location on OBM box using any file-copy tool (like FileZilla or WinSCP) over ssh. Verify that the file exists after copying it in the temp location.</li>
<li>Copy the file to the OMi pod (assuming the zip file was copied to /tmp): <br> <code>kubectl cp /tmp/OMi_Integration_Pack_for_vPV.zip opsbridge1/omi-0:/tmp/OMi_Integration_Pack_for_vPV.zip -c omi</code></li>
<li>Verify that the file is on pod’s /tmp directory: <br><code>kubectl exec omi-0 -c omi -n opsbridge1 ls /tmp</code></li>
<li>Connect to the OBM's pod command line: <br><code>kubectl exec omi-0 -c omi -n opsbridge1 bash –ti</code></li>
<li>Navigate to /tmp: <br><code>cd /tmp</code></li>
<li>Unzip the package: <br><code>unzip *vPV*</code></li>
<li>Navigate to the folder – twice (there are 2 levels of vPV_OMi_Integration folders) <br><code>cd vPV_OMi_Integration</code> <br><code>cd vPV_OMi_Integration</code></li>
<li>Run the installer: <br><code>./vPV_integration_install.sh -i</code></li>
<li>Once the installation is complete, verify that the package was installed successfully on OBM by navigating to <b>Administration &gt; RTSM Administration &gt; Administration &gt; Package Manager</b> and verifying for HPOprvPV package in the list.</li></ol>
<p><b>Step 2: Install the Operations Agent (OA) in CO system and activate it with OBM as monitored node</b>
</p>
<ol><li>See the <a target="1" rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://softwaresupport.softwaregrp.com/km/KM323488">Support Matrices</a> for Cloud Optimizer to know the supported OA versions.</li>
<li>Download the OA installer. See the <a href="./itom/Operations_Agent:12.05/install_guide/_HPc_NewTopic" title="Operations Agent:12.05/install guide/ HPc NewTopic">OA Installation Documentation</a> for the instructions on downloading and installing OA and activating the system with OBM.</li>
<li>After activating the OA installed system with OBM, make sure that on running the <i>ovc</i> command, all the agent processes are in RUNNING state.</li></ol>
<p><b>Step 3:  Deploy Management Aspects/Templates to the CO system and start monitoring</b>
</p>
<ol><li>Log on to OBM user interface and navigate to <b>Administration &gt; Monitoring &gt; Management templates and Aspects &gt; vPV Management Pack</b>.</li>
<li>Deploy <i>vPV Monitor</i> Management Pack on CO. <br>While deploying, in the <b>Parameter Summary</b> section, you may set the parameter <b>Alarm Flag</b> to <code>true</code> for CO to forward VCenter alarms and events.</li></ol>
<p>The Containerized OBM and CO are integrated.
</p>
